Soo  Baically what had to be done, was to create a HashMap within a HashMap.

We have a HashMap (table 1) with Strings (languages) as keys and for the values another HashMap (tables 2). So each key i.e. language has a own HashMap where the nGrams are stored and how often they are used in the language.

What I needed to do, was implement a Instance of HashMap&lt;T&gt; which I had created (in order to use my own hash/probe function and other implemented methods).
But Because the name is the same as the HashMap class from the JDK, it let to confusion as @bohemian had pointed out.

The correct initialization for our Table 1 is:

    LanguageDetector.HashMap&lt;LanguageDetector.HashMap&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; languages;

I forgot to mention, that the key in our HashMap is always a String, but the values only can be whatever we initilize it as.

Here is the complete Code for our school task:

    import java.io.BufferedReader;
