 2. Add the Table annotation before your class entities.
 3. Add the *table* statement into JoinColumn annotation.

The final code:

    @Entity
    @Table(name = &quot;assignment&quot;)
    class Assignment {
      @Id
      private int id;
      
      @Column(name=&quot;assignment_code&quot;)
      private String assignmentCode;
    
      @OneToMany(targetEntity = Review.class, fetch=FetchType.EAGER)
      @JoinColumn(name=&quot;assignment_code&quot;, table=&quot;review&quot;)
      private List&lt;Review&gt; reviews = new ArrayList&lt;Review&gt;();
    }
    
    @Entity
    @Table(name = &quot;review&quot;)
    class Review {
      @Id
      private int id;
      
      @Column(name=&quot;assignment_code&quot;)
      private String assignmentCode;
    }

Seeing your error message, I believe it&#39;s because name of your column is different with your Java variable name, usually I will name my column on the database something like `assignment_code` and this column was references to join between Review and Assignment. 

My first suggestion is, if my hunch correct about different naming between database column and Java variable,  put `@Column(name = &quot;assignment_code&quot;)` above `private String assignmentCode`.

Second, I think you have a mistake when define `@OneToMany` relations. I will do something like this on `Assignment` class (I assume you want something like _Unidirectional_ ,seeing from your code).

    @OneToMany(cascade = CascadeType.ALL, fetch=FetchType.LAZY, orphanRemoval = true)
    @JoinColumn(name=&quot;assignment_code&quot;)
    private List&lt;Review&gt; reviews = new ArrayList&lt;Review&gt;();

Reminder, on `@JoinColumn` the name was the __references column__ name on the database and __not Java variable name__.

